</table>
<p><b>Bees</b> are flying <a href="/wiki/Insect" title="Insect">insects</a> closely related to <a href="/wiki/Wasp" title="Wasp">wasps</a> and <a href="/wiki/Ant" title="Ant">ants</a>. Bees are a <a href="/wiki/Monophyly" title="Monophyly">monophyletic</a> lineage within the superfamily <b><a href="/wiki/Apoidea" title="Apoidea">Apoidea</a></b>, presently classified by the unranked taxon name <b>Anthophila</b>. There are nearly 20,000 known species of bees in nine recognized families,<sup id="cite_ref-Danforthetal2006_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Danforthetal2006-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> though many are undescribed and the actual number is probably higher. They are found on every continent except <a href="/wiki/Antarctica" title="Antarctica">Antarctica</a>, in every habitat on the planet that contains insect-pollinated <a href="/wiki/Flowering_plant" title="Flowering plant">flowering plants</a>.</p>
